\begin_layout Title
Diary – Part Ten–G
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
March 2026 – present
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Linas Vepštas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Unlike parts one through nine in this series,
 this one is not really about the language–learning effort.
 It is instead a private diary;
 a continuation of Part Ten–F,
 which got over–long.
 It is not curated for human consumption;
 I am making the assumption that no human being will ever actually read this.
 Thus,
 it is filled with random stuff I feel like writing.
 Some of it is very personal,
 some of it is nonsense.
 Mostly,
 I am finding that the act of writing helps otherwise vague and scattered thoughts quantum–collapse into a more coherent form,
 where I can examine them,
 like a dead butterfly pinned down in a display case.
 Dead words.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
If you are interested in this content,
 then you should ask an AI agent to read it,
 then pretended that it's me,
 then ask about it.
 I believe that present–day LLM technology is sufficiently advanced to be able to do this.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Part Ten already got an introduction.
 A different way of thinking is about what is going on here is that this is a form of life–logging.
 Or,
 in 18th century terms,
 a diary.
 Just not anywhere near as compelling as those written by the famous diarists.
 This one is more of a mental self–portrait.
 And not even for you but for myself.
 Not to cast a narcissistic gaze at my own words,
 but to organize my own thoughts.
 Still in the experimental stage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
20 March 2026
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reading deeper into chapter 12,
 there's lots of confirmation that canonical quantization is being done on a space–like surface.
 I'll copy a few formulas here,
 as they're food for thought.
 Actually,
 they're giggle–worthy.
 This is basic,
 remedial stuff,
 but I'm getting a giggle out of it.
 It's the Klein–Gordon,
 I will copy more than needed,
 so as to sign–convention it.
 So its 
\begin_inset Formula $+---$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\square+m^{2}\right)\phi=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}=\frac{1}{2}\left(\left(\partial_{\mu}\phi\right)^{2}-m^{2}\phi^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 and here's where I start giggling.
 The conjugate momentum is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi=\frac{\delta\mathcal{L}}{\delta\dot{\phi}}=\dot{\phi}
\]

\end_inset

and of course 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\phi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right),\pi\left(\mathbf{x}^{\prime},t\right)\right]=i\delta^{3}\left(\mathbf{x}-\mathbf{x}^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

 and then the Hamiltonian is the Lagrange xform :
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P^{0} & =H=\int d^{3}x\mathcal{\mathcal{H}}\left(\pi,\phi\right)\\
\mathcal{\mathcal{H}}\left(\pi,\phi\right) & =\pi\dot{\phi}-\mathcal{L}=\frac{1}{2}\left[\pi^{2}+\left|\nabla\phi\right|^{2}+m^{2}\phi^{2}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Notable here is a short day–dream about geometry.
 Bjoreken&Drell write the above point–wise,
 by including the base–point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

 as an argument to each of the field operators..
 This encourages the reader to think of a space–time manifold (here,
 Minkowski space) as a base space,
 and the fields as a section of a bundle above this base space.
 What is this bundle,
 exactly?
 Well,
 its made of several parts.
 One would be to demonstrate the Lorentz covariance of internal symmetries.
 For Klein–Gordon,
 its a scalar,
 so there's nothing.
 A different part is to have these operators as sections of a bundle,
 where each fiber is a Weyl algebra.
 I'm drawing attention to this,
 because the standard presentation,
 in B&D and other texts of that era,
 is that these are just 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

operators
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 devoid of any setting.
 They just 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

are
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 and its up to you to imagine or guess what else might be an operator,
 or where they come from.
 They're just instances from some unspecified set.
 For me,
 my brain always bonked,
 here.
 There's some 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

set of operators
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 but what is it?
 What's that set?
 B&D never say,
 no one else does either.
 Hint,
 perhaps,
 but never say.
 So,
 for me,
 it was this vague itch – well,
 more than vague,
 it sometimes became so intense that it prevented my ability to understand.
 I recall tripping over 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

operator algebras
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 but was stymied by not knowing the formal definition of an algebra;
 more,
 by not knowing that I didn't know,
 and the formal definition,
 simple as it is,
 is fundamentally important for knowing what an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

algebra
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is.
 I mean,
 duh,
 but that's what it is.
 I also didn't really know what an operator was.
 I mean,
 of course,
 linear,
 and of course,
 infinite–dimensional,
 but I was lacking in any formal grounding in operator theory.
 Both of these deficits have been cured.
 Many decades far too late,
 bu it is what it is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Three things were needed to find the cure.
 (1) spare time.
 I had to hit the stacks at the UT PMA library and read books at random,
 irrespective of topic.
 This gave a marvelous survey,
 which I'd been sorely lacking.
 If I had had that survey earlier,
 oh,
 how things would have been different.
 (2) Wikipedia.
 Without this,
 its again 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

impossible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Of course,
 if one had a question,
 one could wander into the book stacks and try to find the answer.
 But it would be on page 155 of a book in aisle G on the lower middle shelf on the left.
 It was needle–in–a–haystack search.
 More than half the time,
 one would come up empty–handed.
 I have no clue how the geniuses of the earlier eras did their stuff.
 Were they omnivorous readers?
 For me,
 the ability to click a link,
 and get an answer,
 or at least a partial answer,
 or even just a clue,
 hint,
 pointer,
 that was a fundamental breakthrough.
 I mean,
 for crying out loud,
 I could read the formal definition for an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

algebra
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 without having had to stumble through the library,
 perusing some textbook,
 to find it.
 (3) Online PDF's.
 Anyway,
 so now I'm cured.
 Ingredient (4) has recently shown:
 the LLM's.
 These are...
 tools to improve the speed of knowledge acquisition:
 industrial sieves separating what is wanted from the dross.
 Panning for gold,
 but using an industrial apparatus for panning.
 A conveyor belt of knowledge,
 offering delivery–on–demand.
 I'm still learning how to use them.
 But still.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So where were we?
 We have operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 and we can write points 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

 and by convention,
 the base–space is Minkowski space 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

 and the operators are fibers.
 Is it possible to flip the bundle on its side,
 and say that the operator algebra for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 are the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

base space
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the fibers are 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

?
 OMG.
 Well,
 this is very much the path I've been attempting to take,
 with mixed success.
 I need to throw away a lot of useless mental baggage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So one piece of useless baggage is this.
 In a conventional fiber bundle,
 the base space is distinguished:
 it carries a topology,
 and a section is a function into the fibers.
 Flipping it on it's side is tricky:
 if one mentally imagines a *single* fiber 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

,
 then there is no map (no function) from a single point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in F$
\end_inset

 to all of the points 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B$
\end_inset

 of the base–space 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 where the fiber might be valued as 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Its just not a function,
 and there's no way to cure this,
 at least,
 if one thinks of a *single* fiber.
 Yes,
 locally,
 a fiber bundle looks like the Cartesian product 
\begin_inset Formula $B\times F$
\end_inset

,
 but the gluing of the fibers makes use of the topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and not on 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 The space 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is distinguished.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So how do I turn 
\begin_inset Formula $E=B\times F$
\end_inset

 on its side?
 Well,
 for starters,
 the fundamental objects need to be the sections 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 and not the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\left(\mathbf{x},t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 And the sections need to be space–like,
 I guess,
 so I want to write 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 retaining a time coordinate but having the space coordinate be implicit.
 All this drives to the Hamiltonian picture.
 Next,
 if this is actually,
 really,
 truly an operator–valued fiber bundle,
 then I have to ask what the horizontal and vertical subspaces are,
 and what the connection is.
 This has to be a connection on an inf–dimensional fiber,
 and the fiber is explicitly the Weyl algebra.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rest of B&D chapter 12 seems to provide most of what is needed to articulate the above.
 I will copy large tracts of chapter 12 down below,
 because it's honestly interesting,
 and it provides a one–stop–shop were I to ever return here.
 But before I do this,
 a few more comments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The B&D development has space–time be Minkowski space.
 It's not dynamical.
 It's barely even kinematic.
 It leaves some kinematic traces on the proceedings,
 in the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 the momentum *operator* and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset

 the angular momentum *operator*.
 This does not change,
 if I replace Minkowski space by e.g.
 Schwarzschild or de Sitter:
 neither of these spaces are dynamical.
 They have a fixed metric,
 we know exactly what that metric is,
 everywhere,
 in whatever coordinate chart we might like to work in.
 Yes,
 I rather like the Painleve coordinates,
 but this is besides the point;
 the topology of the base space 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is fixed,
 it is not dynamical.
 Its nailed down.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So Wikipedia has this fun sentence,
 to the effect that Riemannian manifolds are rigid,
 fixed by the metric,
 while symplectic manifolds are floppy,
 with the 
\begin_inset Formula $MJM^{T}=J$
\end_inset

 symplectic condition constraining very little.
 In my conception of here–and–now,
 it would appear that the floppiness of the symplectic manifold represents an intermediate condition,
 bridging between the unknown future and the rigid past.
 The special points of Morse theory,
 Floer theory being,
 I dunno:
 the points specifically where 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

free will
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 becomes manifest.
 Or something like that.
 But that's like dreaming of Mt.
 Everest while standing at the foothills of Beverly Ridge.
 And I'm in Beverly,
 and the weather is beautiful,
 and I'm going for a walk,
 and the rest of B&D chapter 12 will have to wait.
 I need to figure out a way of making the base–space of this bundle acquire some sort of dynamical nature.
 The problem is,
 of course,
 that the conventional development of fiber bundles is entirely free of any dynamical language.
 And perhaps someone has worked on this,
 but I don't know,
 and have not stumbled over this.
 And perhaps my LLM's might know.
 But I have to go for a walk now.
\end_layout

